## Core Engineering Directives (IDGAF Execution Rules)

### 1. Strict Native AOT Compliance
*   Every line of C# code must be Native AOT-friendly.
*   Absolutely NO reflection (`System.Reflection`), NO dynamic IL generation (`System.Reflection.Emit`), and NO dependency on dynamic runtime type resolution.
*   Use compile-time alternatives (e.g., compile-time evaluated `Unsafe.SizeOf<T>()` instead of `Marshal.SizeOf`).

### 2. High-Performance, Zero-Allocation Mindset
*   On hot paths, enforce strict allocation-free patterns: utilize `ReadOnlySpan<byte>`, `ValueTask`, and rent scratch buffers via `ArrayPool<char>` / `ArrayPool<byte>`.
*   Ensure explicit layout alignment of memory-mapped structures (natural power-of-two alignment to prevent ARM64 hardware alignment faults; do not enforce `Pack = 1` rules without addressing hardware boundaries).

### 3. Secure Sandbox Mindset
*   Design code under the assumption of Least Privilege execution (`loomd` user) with zero OS capabilities.
*   Any pointer manipulation (`AcquirePointer`) must be wrapped within native `SafeBuffer` or custom `SafeHandle` wrappers as strict resource reclamation boundaries to prevent memory leaks.

